 G-men and the looming threat of prison if Frankie doesn’t talk. But since talking has never been one of Frankie’s strengths, he copes as he always has: by trying to tough it out on his own. Calling to mind such gritty poets of the urban scene as George V. Higgins and Nelson Algren, Time for Frankie Coolin is both a psychological thriller and a ’70s Chicago period piece that shines a surprisingly sympathetic light on the often ignored stories of the people who lived, worked, and died at the city’s margins.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aLandlordszIllinoiszChicagovFiction. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh  apsychological fiction, historical thrillers, powerful novel, distinctive voices, compelling characters, suspense, late 20th-century chicago, race relations, racism, racial issues, politics, political, politicians, landlord, abandoned buildings, black tenants, tough guy, family man, arson, g-men, prison time, urban scenes, period piece, sympathetic light, marginalized people, poverty, poor, inner city troubles, crime, criminals.1 aSavage, Bill, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSavage, Bill.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311069043940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226202785423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226202785/original  a978-3-11-069043-9  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aGBV-deGruyter-alles